table-0176-349.caption: List of episodes
data: Chris visits the dressing rooms, master control room and reception before talking to programme editor David McKeith and breakfast presenter/producer Lynn Stewart.
Chris hasn't taken off his studio make-up
The second one where we go behind the scenes
Chris goes around the headquarters once again and also reveals the staff members who are not overly keen about appearing on camera.
Norman talks to Lynsey Macintosh, clubbing correspondent for STV.
The one where the sun's shining (finally!)
A look inside the satellite truck, a lookahead to the 6pm show with Rachel Innes and another unsuccessful attempt by Chris to spend more than 20 seconds in the studio gallery...
Programme editor Alan Cowie looksahead to the 6pm programme whilst Andrea meets the new work experience guy...a Dalek.
Norman welcomes newcomer journalist, Louise Cowie.
Kirstin presents her first blog with a look at photos of Grampian/STV North presenters as they were in the past.
Norman presents the blog from the financial department.
The desks in the newsroom come under the spotlight of Northern Exposure. Plus, a lookahead to the 6pm programme with Ross Govans and the return of reporter Steven Godden.
Norman talks to Euan Wemyss on his first day of reporting and to programme editor David McKeith on his first day back from holidays.
A look into the relationship between Chris and the technical crew.
Andrea explains the reasoning behind a blooper from last night and talks to reporter David Marsland. Plus, a lookahead to tonight's main story with reporter Sharon Donaldson.

Andrea expresses her frustration at the lack of crisps in the vending machines...only to be interrupted by the scene of a burning car on a road beside the studios. Meanwhile, David McKeith looks ahead to tonight's programme.
Andrea looks back at Euan's dancing from last night, talks to Sharon Donaldson and explains the lack of blogs.
By request from the forums, Norman tours the kitchen. Meanwhile, Ross Govans shares a tale about the smell of the room in question.
The one with all the mistakes

Give or take one or two mistakes, Chris eavesdrops in on the banter of Kirstin and Norman, talks to Rachel Innes about tonight's show, shows us an outtake from a festival and has a chat about a special report with David Marsland (who gets a kiss from Kirstin).
Another jaunt around the newsroom with Chris, including another chat with Lynsey Macintosh.
Norman visits the Commercial Production Department of STV North.
Programme editor Rachel Innes gives a rundown of some of the stories for the 6pm programme and Business correspondent Cheryl Paul looks ahead to an oil exhibition.
After a lengthy break, the blog returns with some chat about the holidays of reporter/presenter Laura Goodwin.
Norman revisits the Commercial Production Department to take a look at their self-styled tat corner.
Kirstin answers questions from the STV website's forums in an episode that began the feedback show, Ask Kirstin. Plus, a lookback at the title sequences used by North Tonight over the years.
Kirstin visits the archives to answer more queries from the forums.
A behind-the-scenes look at the production gallery for the Tayside opt-out, based in Aberdeen. Norman is joined by director Bill Shand.
After a long absence, Chris returns to the blog.
Nicola in the newsroom has had a scare from a spider. Norman goes on the trail to find it.
It's 45 minutes to go until North Tonight goes on air and Chris reports on the buzz of the newsroom ahead of on-air time...or lack of it as the case may be.
Norman is joined by chief subtitler Susanne Reid for an interview.
Chris goes around the newsroom to hear a few jokes, funny or otherwise, from STV North staff.
STV North commercial producer James Cameron attempts to break the Guinness World Record for eating three cream crackers.
Norman tours the other premises to be found at Craigshaw Business Park (the location of STV North's studios) and visits Petrofac Training, where Hallowe'en has come a day early.
Norman talks to producer Bob Kenyon about the Scots Gaelic-language output of STV North and the possibility of a new digital Gaelic channel.
It'll be alright on the North Tonight

Another episode of the regular series Ask Kirstin, featuring classic outtakes from North Tonight' over the years. Plus, more of the forum's questions, an old promo for North Tonight and more memories from the ITV Telethons.
The first of a two-part special looking back at STV Tayside's news coverage in 2007, beginning with a look at some of the key stories and images from the last 12 months.
The Tayside review continues with a look at the more uplifting highlights from 2007.
Northern Exposure signs off for 2007 with more bloopers from the archives.
The first 2008 edition of the feedback/archive series, beginning with a quick-fire round up of questions from the forums.
The man flu has been going round the newsroom as sports correspondent Tyrone Smith and programme editor David McKeith know only too well. They talk to Norman about the past few days.
A rapid round-up of questions, a special competition to win STV goody bags plus an appearance from STV North's senior camera operator, Alistair Watt.
Kirstin takes time off from her question-answering duties to provide an insight into the quiet weekends at STV North's studios in Aberdeen.
A special short episode as Kirstin and resources co-ordinator Louise Steel draws the winners for the big goody bag competition.

Kirstin announces the winner of the Grampian Television brolly competition, but not before answering more questions and taking a second look at the first day of broadcasting from the studios at Craigshaw Business Park.
Aberdeen take on Bayern Munich in the UEFA Cup tomorrow night. Norman looks ahead to the match with sports correspondent Tyrone Smith.
Norman gets with the times and joins STV clubbing correspondent Lynsey Macintosh for an update on the station's clubbing website.
Kirstin returns with another quick-fire edition of the feedback series. Plus, a glance of Sarah Mack's outdoor lifestyle series, The Great Outdoors.
A special report on how hawks are being used by STV North to stop seagulls from nesting near the Tullos studios. Norman is joined by hawks' expert Ian Caine.
This weekend, Tyrone Smith and Norman Macleod will be taking part in a rowing race against local media rivals. Chris talks to the duo about the challenge.
Chris and the North Tonight team talk baby names...and with good reason. N.B. This edition was recorded on 5 March 2008.

A special late edition of the feature series. Tonight, Kirstin is joined by Grampian TV legend Alan Cowie for a special interview and to answer a few questions for the forumers. And before they run fresh out of time, there's also a clip of the Nicky Campbell gameshow, You'd Better Believe It.
Norman Macleod, Rachel Innes and Nicola Barron lookahead to another frantic week of news in Northern Scotland and address the issues that arise with interviews in foreign languages.

James Cameron, commercial producer for STV North and one-time contender for the cream crackers eating world record, is bidding adieu. He talks about his time at the station whilst Norman hears from the advertising staff he's leaving behind.
By request, Kirstin delves into more photos from the archives. Also this week, clips from The Electric Theatre Show, Grampian Weekend (with Sarah Mack & Michael Crow) and The Craig Millar Files.

Senior staff cameraman Alistair Watt (well known for his appearances on Ask Kirstin) and freelance cameraman Terry Farquharson join Norman for a lesuirely chat about how their job has changed through the years.
Last night, North Tonight featured a woman who had banned herself from shopping. But are their any shopaholics within the STV North newsteam? The answers may not surprise you.
Seán Batty special (or A different outlook)
How well has Jo Farrow settled in at STV? Norman finds out.
It's been a long time coming but Kirstin is back for a quick-fire round up of questions from the forumers.
STV North's jack of all trades
Norman talks to one of the station's unsung heroes, courier Russell Orchard.

A record-breaking edition of the feedback series as Kirstin presents 22 minutes of questions, photos and a clip of the recent Gaelic programme on the Snowman Rally in Inverness. Plus, a bit of help from studio director Bill Shand, cameraman Alistair Watt and new guest presenter Louise Steel.
After a false start, Norman and sports correspondent Tyrone Smith talk football once again as the SPL season nears its climax.

You've seen her on Ask Kirstin and now, production journalist Louise Steel steps into the spotlight as the new stand-in host for Northern Exposure. Today, Louise is joined by resources supervisor/Tayside opt director Bill Shand and sound operator Rudy Macleod.
This week, Kirstin features photos of former continuity announcers and takes a look at Grampian TV's operations around the time of the buyout by Scottish Television. Plus, more questions.
Louise Steel takes on hosting duties again as George Dunoon, Norman Macleod, Lynne Rankin (née Stewart) and Claire Stewart share some fashion tips. N.B. This edition was recorded on 30 May 2008.

A very busy day means there's no time to run through the questions and requests. So tonight, Kirstin takes a look at a couple of the archive documents, including one of the few pieces of material remaining from Grampian's opening day of transmission - the scripts.
STV head of news Gordon MacMillan talks about the performance of STV News during the first half of 2008 and what's to come in the near future.
It's Friday the 13th and there's no prizes for guessing the topic as Louise takes control of the blog once again.
Kirstin presents more quick-fire questions from the North Tonight studio. N.B. This blog was recorded on 23 June 2008.
Kirstin visits the news VT library for more questions and introduces opening sequences from Wize Up, The Video Show, Scotland's Larder and Unsolved.
What passes for the summer climate at Tullos leads Norman to ask the newsroom staff where they would rather be today.
Studio director Michael Armstrong guests as Kirstin introduces the second of her profile interviews.
Time for Kirstin to sign off before her summer holidays. But before she goes, there's time for some questions and the latest profile interview, featuring Louise Steel.

Following a recent poll which puts the Scottish accent third of favourite accents, Norman asks for the opinion of the newsroom on the matter. Viewers are warned that this programme contains sexual harassment.

A chance finding of a leaflet in an old ITV Yearbook reveals an old tradition at GTV - staff pantomimes starring amongst others, Gaelic producer Bob Kenyon and chief editor of North Tonight, Donald John McDonald. Here they talk to Louise Steel about 'Malice in Wonderland'. N.B. This episode was recorded on 31 July 2008.
A catch up in STV North's burgeoning commercial department features a quick chat with chief commercial producer Paul Farquharshon and a meet up with their latest recruit, Calum Youngson.
Tonight, Kirstin endeavours to answer further queries and meets Rebecca Morris, a work experience student at STV North with strong links hailing back to the Grampian days of old.

Regional output, Andrea Brymer and technical problems are on the agenda tonight along with a tryout in front of the camera for work experience girl Rebecca Morris as she interviews commercial producer Paul Farquarshon.

It is not every day that you'll find the likes of North Tonight's chief editor or one of the sales assistants receiving massages. But with consultants from Aveda Spa based in the meeting room at the Tullos studios today, obviously things are a little different. Louise describes the scene.
A late shift for Kirstin means a midweek edition of the feedback show including the usual mix of questions and a snippet of gardening show Grow for It.
Stories of holidays in France, the Scottish Borders and Borneo, courtesy of Norman Macleod, Rachel Innes and Jill Mowat.

A weekend shift and a free camera offers Kirstin the chance to host the 1st anniversary edition of Ask Kirstin from an empty newsroom to try to answer questions with minimum help and to offer her opinion on a proposed revamp of the show. N.B. This blog was recorded on 27 September 2008.
Norman talks sport, but this time with freelance journalist Dave Donaldson.
Lynsey Macintosh is preparing for a parachute sky dive for the first time and all in the name of charity. Louise, her fellow production journalist, chats to her ahead of the big jump.
Another work experience student appears at STV North in the form of prospective camera operator Vicky MacLean from the Isle of Skye - her mentor, Alistair Watt, appears to offer some comment.
In a late, late edition of the blog tonight, Norman says goodbye for now to sales manager Jane Melhuish as she goes on maternity leave.
On Wear it Pink Day, Louise goes around the STV North headquarters in the name of finding out who has decided to go pink this Halloween.
KG returns with another fast-paced rundown of queries.

A far-from-technically-minded Kirstin Gove visits the Central Apparatus Room and studio gallery for questions on transmitters, picture format codes, editing and so on. But will the clip of social affairs programme Get Real materialise the second time round?
STV North has been sent a DVD from an anonymous viewer containing plasticine models and footage of squirrels. Norman takes the liberty of showing it to Northern Exposure viewers.

Kirstin makes her way through a sudden mid-show pause, a brief cameo from Alistair Watt and not a lot of preparation time to introduce a late edition of the popular feedback show. And will it be third time lucky for Get Real?
The countdown to digital switchover in Northern Scotland continued today with a press launch at the studios of STV North. Norman Macleod reports.
It's the final edition of the year and a poorly Kirstin limits her Christmas special to a brief look at what the forum is asking.

Norman kicks off STV's video blogging for 2009 by starting the year's Northern Exposure with the news team's annual resolutions. Meanwhile, Cheryl Paul is looking into what impact the global financial crisis is having on the region.
It's said that today is Blue Monday, the most depressing day of the year. But does it ring true in the North Tonight newsroom?
Norman introduces another student on placement with STV North - Nikki Stevenson from Robert Gordon University.
A lookback at this year's Up Helly Aa celebrations in Shetland with Louise Cowie.
A very late and very brief Ask Kirstin as all energies go into preparing for North Tonight at six.
Ask Kirstin: Will on the Web
Web editor and STV Central blogs regular, Will Springer, turns up in Aberdeen to guest on the final edition of Ask Kirstin.

Since December last year, STV North's weekly News Review for the deaf has been made available online. One of the review's interpreters, Bert Smale from the Aberdeen Deaf Society, talks to programme producer Norman Macleod about this addition to STV's video site.
After a humiliating defeat last year, Norman and Tyrone are looking to outdo their local media rivals in next weekend's annual boat race on the river Dee. Time for some training...
Highlights and post-match comment as Norman and Tyrone triumph in the Aberdeen Media Rowing Challenge. Meanwhile, Claire Stewart rues over what happened to her and Jill Mowatt during the heats.
Norman makes his excuses for the lack of Northern Exposure and meets Eva Mowat, cousin of Jill, on 'Bring Your Child to Work Day'.
Many know them as Laura Goodwin and Chris Harvey but tonight, Norman, they're going to be Geri Halliwell and Gene Simmons!
Last October, viewers first got to hear about Lynsey Macintosh's parachute jump for charity. Unfortunately, it was cancelled six times - but last weekend, it was seventh time lucky.

As clubbing editor-in-chief at STV, Lynsey Macintosh loves Ibiza. So much so, she's leaving STV North for three months. Louise sends her off and meets her summer replacement, Fiona, on the very last Northern Exposure blog.

data: The status quo is shaken up when egalitarian Rire discovers the Sevolite Empire and exposes all to irrefutable proof that a commoner sword dancer is actually racist Sevildom's long-lost crown prince, Amel. Relationships destined to influence history are forged, and the stage set for power struggles in Amel's name.

In the wake of tragic setbacks, progressive leaders find the strength, through friendships, to establish a new order at court, negotiated by the apparently powerless Amel. One of them is the legendary Ameron, returned from time slip.

Erien's returns to his home world to champion his Reetion foster father, and causes the collapse of the uneasy truce among Sevildom's leadership in a series of shocks that end in sordid horror for some but overall affirms the power of Okal Rel to keep the peace for all.

Rire resists diplomatic relations with Sevildom by claiming the moral high ground, thus straining the patience of House Nersal and dragging Amel through intense public interest in him as a victim of Sevildom.

Rejected by Erien, and challenged by Perry to realize the dream of making the Blue Demish a court power, Amel competes with Luthan to win Demora in a bizarre competition to identify which of them is 'nicer'. Luthan struggles with her love of Erien and Vretla just wants to get pregnant by either Pureblood. When Amel's new body guard, Alivda, chucks Vretla out of Amel's bedroom, she joins Erien on a mission to rescue his young nephew, Leksan, who is kidnapped by a rival clan. Amel and Erien struggle to cooperate for the greater good while competing for love and for oaths.

Amel must appease the League of Demish Women for the Betterment of Men, aided by Princess Samanda O'Pearl. Although Amel is making progress with becoming respectable, Midlord liege Ilse Marin, from a family long loyal to Ev’rel, is reluctant to swear to him. Instead, she gets involved with Erien's Academy of Science for Sevolites where she meets Horth Nersal. Erien's work and Horth's literal mindedness, get Horth and Ilse into big trouble with the Lion Reach Demish on a mission to bring staff for the Reetion Embassy to Gelion. Everything comes to a head at the first Cultural Exchange with the Reetions, on Barmi II.
